<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>give someone a ticking-off • tick someone off</xh5><p> <i>give someone a ticking-off</i>—(coll.) scold or reprimand a person: The referee <u>gave Mike a ticking-off</u>. Not that he cared.</p><p> <i>tick someone off—</i>1. put a mark by smb.’s name on a list: I ask each kid one question, <u>ticking them off</u> as they answer. 2. mark smb. as a potential object for vengeance or hostility: If anyone starts fault-finding he is immediately “<u>ticked off</u>.” 3. <i>= give someone a ticking-off: </i>He was “<u>ticked off</u> ” by one of the boys for leaving his car unlocked and complete with ignition key. 4. <i>(U.S. sl.)</i> annoy or anger a person: It <u>ticks me off</u> when I have to study and somebody makes noise.</p> </entry>
